1 Intro and Data Loading

One of the deadliest malignant illnesses, pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma (PDAC), which accounts for 90% of all pancreatic cancers, has an overall five-year survival rate of 8% for all stages combined and is the fourth highest cause of cancer-related death worldwide. Two frequently used tumor cell lines for in vitro research of PDAC carcinogenesis are MIAPaCa-2 and PANC-1. There is an urgent need to better understand the molecular pathophysiology of PDAC. Although PANC-1 and MIA PaCa-2 are not well differentiated, their physical characteristics differ significantly. For instance, there are significant molecular disparity between PANC-1, which is generated from a patient with metastasis, and MIA PaCa-2, whose patient’s metastatic status is unknown. Hence, it is of great value to explore the difference between these two cell lines to potentiall identify genes for tareted therapetics for PANC-1.

This project is aimed to conduct a differential expression analysis on the transcriptome of three MIAPaCa-2 and three PANC-1 cell samples using DESeq2. The raw count data of RNA expression of these samples are obtained from the GEO database on NCBI (https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/geo/query/acc.cgi?acc=GSE169758).

count_matrix = read.table("GSE169758_count_matrix.txt", header=TRUE)

2 Running DESeq2

DESeq2 is very simple programming wise at a base level. We first instansiate the data set that DESeq2 reads and then run the code.

deseq_dataset = DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = count_matrix, colData = coldata, design= ~condition)
deseq_dataset
## class: DESeqDataSet 
## dim: 63677 6 
## metadata(1): version
## assays(1): counts
## rownames(63677): ENSG00000000003 ENSG00000000005 ... ENSG00000273492
##   ENSG00000273493
## rowData names(0):
## colnames(6): Mic1 Mic2 ... Pan2 Pan3
## colData names(1): condition
deseq_dataset_mean = DESeq(deseq_dataset,  # the dataset used 
                           fitType = 'mean',  # use the mean of gene-wise dispersion estimates
                           minReplicatesForReplace = 7,  # the minimum number of replicates required in order to use replaceOutliers on a sample
                           parallel = TRUE)  # Enable parallization using milti-threading
## estimating size factors
## estimating dispersions
## gene-wise dispersion estimates: 6 workers
## mean-dispersion relationship
## final dispersion estimates, fitting model and testing: 6 workers

We set minReplicatesForReplace, to 7 because that was the default in the paper. However, here we only have 3 samples genes worth of information by condition so outlying genes will just be dropped from the analysis.

In these results we see baseMean, which is the mean of normlized counts across all samples, we see the log2foldchange which is the log2fold change (MLE) Pan vs Mic, the lfcSE, which is the standard error, stat which is the Wald test statistic for Pan vs Mic, the p value for significant difference between Pan vs Mic, and the adjusted pvalue which is the pvalue adjusted for multiple comparisons.

We see above that, 17% of genes tested in our project are marked up-regulated and 14% of them are down-regulated. Only 0.034% of genes are outliers. We have a lot, 24%, of low-expressed genes in the in the result.

table(result$padj<0.05)
## 
## FALSE  TRUE 
## 15660  8608
result_up = result[which(result$log2FoldChange >= 1 & result$pvalue < 0.05),]
result_down = result[which(result$log2FoldChange <= -1 & result$pvalue < 0.05),]
result_total = rbind(result_up,result_down)
write.csv(result_total, file = "DEG_Mic_vs_PANC.csv")

Here we see there are 8608 genes that have a padj value less than 0.05. We will define upregulated genes as ones who have a log2FoldChange >= 1 & pvalue < 0.05. We will define down regulated genes as ones who have a log2FoldChange <= -1 & pvalue < 0.05. We save these results to a csv.

Now, we can do this again but utilizing DESeq2’s shrinkage.

dds <- DESeq(deseq_dataset)
## estimating size factors
## estimating dispersions
## gene-wise dispersion estimates
## mean-dispersion relationship
## final dispersion estimates
## fitting model and testing
res <- results(dds)
resultsNames(dds)
## [1] "Intercept"            "condition_Pan_vs_Mic"
resLFC <- lfcShrink(dds, coef="condition_Pan_vs_Mic", type = "normal")
## using 'normal' for LFC shrinkage, the Normal prior from Love et al (2014).
## 
## Note that type='apeglm' and type='ashr' have shown to have less bias than type='normal'.

We can now start to visualize our data, we start with making a heat map.

select = order(rowMeans(counts(deseq_dataset_mean, normalized = TRUE)), decreasing = TRUE)[1:20]
normal_deseq_dataset_mean = normTransform(deseq_dataset_mean)
df = as.data.frame(colData(deseq_dataset_mean)[,c("condition", "sizeFactor")])
pheatmap(assay(normal_deseq_dataset_mean)[select,], cluster_rows=FALSE, show_rownames=TRUE, cluster_cols=TRUE, annotation_col=df)

This plot seems to make sense to us. Between the biological replicates, there seems to be concordance. We see some genes with blue in Mic group and genes with bright red in the Mic group as well. We note that Mic2 has the largest size factor.

Next, we can pick a gene with high log2FoldChange and plotted its expression level among all samples. According to recent publications, FOXA2 is a tumor suppressor in pancreatic cancer and it controls the cis-regulatory networks of pancreatic cancer cells in a differentiation grade-specific manner. Hence, it contributes to the heterogeneity of PDAC cells and should be carefully considered when testing drugs on different cell lines.

d = data.frame(t(subset(count_matrix,rownames(count_matrix)=="ENSG00000125798")))
condition = factor(rep(c('Mic', 'Pan'), each = 3))
ggplot(d, aes(x = condition, y = ENSG00000125798, color = condition))+
  geom_point(position=position_jitter(w=0.2,h=0))+
  theme_bw()+
  ggtitle("The expression level of FOXA2")+
  theme(plot.title=element_text(hjust=0.5))

In the plot above, we see that FOXA2 does not express in the MIA PaCa-2 cell line but is highly expressed in the PANC-1 cell line.

Here we made a heatmap of the distance matrix that gives us an overview over similarities and dissimilarities between samples.

plotDispEsts(dds)

Plotting the dispersion estimates is a useful diagnostic. The dispersion plot below is typical, with the final estimates shrunk from the gene-wise estimates towards the fitted estimates. Some gene-wise estimates are flagged as outliers and not shrunk towards the fitted value, (this outlier detection is described in the manual page for estimateDispersionsMAP). The amount of shrinkage can be more or less than seen here, depending on the sample size, the number of coefficients, the row mean and the variability of the gene-wise estimates.

In the volcano plot, the red dots we see represent the DEGs that pass the thresholds for FDR and Log Fold Change. The genes on the left side of the volcano are down-regulated genes and the genes on the right side are up-regulated genes. This plot can show what the top genes are by P value and also which of them have bigger fold changes.

Conclusion

Using DESeq2, we used the transcriptomes of three MIAPaCa-2 and three PANC-1 cell samples in this experiment to analyze the differences in expression. More than 7000 DEGs were found, and the gene with the largest Log2FoldChange was confirmed. After that, we performed a quality check and presented our findings using certain visualization tools. The upregulated and downregulated genes in PANC-1 should be looked at in a systematic order based on LFC or shrunken LFC and their downstream protein translations should be researched next to potentially aid in targeted therapies for pancreatic cancer.
